The paper deals with computational complexity theory and lower bounds on switching networks for directed connectivity, which are topics typically studied in the cs.CC (Computational Complexity) and cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) sub-categories. The use of monotone and certain-knowledge switching networks suggests a focus on Boolean functions and logic, which could also place the paper in the cs.LG (Machine Learning) sub-category. The investigation of a specific set of inputs and the demonstration of a polynomially-sized monotone switching network could be seen as related to information theory and coding, potentially placing the paper in the cs.IT (Information Theory) sub-category. Finally, the use of switching networks and directed connectivity could also be relevant to the cs.SI (Social and Information Networks) sub-category, although this is less likely given the focus on theoretical complexity results.
